To get a copy of the entire page HTML from a webpage that no longer exists but is still open in your Chrome browser, you can use the following JavaScript code in the browser's console:

```javascript
document.documentElement.outerHTML;
```

This code retrieves the outer HTML of the `<html>` element, which includes the entire webpage's HTML structure.

Here's how you can use it:

1. Open the Chrome Developer Tools by pressing `Ctrl + Shift + I` (Windows/Linux) or `Cmd + Option + I` (Mac).

2. Switch to the "Console" tab in the Developer Tools.

3. Type or paste the following code into the console and press Enter:
   ```javascript
   document.documentElement.outerHTML;
   ```

4. The console will display the entire HTML of the webpage as a string.

5. To copy the HTML, you can right-click on the output in the console and select "Copy" or manually select the text and copy it.

Alternatively, if you want to save the HTML directly to a file, you can use the following code:

```javascript
let html = document.documentElement.outerHTML;
let blob = new Blob([html], {type: "text/html"});
let a = document.createElement("a");
a.href = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
a.download = "webpage.html";
a.click();
```

This code creates a Blob object containing the HTML, generates a temporary URL for the Blob, creates a new `<a>` element with the URL as the `href` attribute and a `download` attribute set to the desired filename, and then programmatically clicks the link to trigger the download of the HTML file.

Remember to execute this code in the browser's console while the webpage is still open, as the HTML will not be available once the page is closed or navigated away from.

